SIMPLE: silence
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Silence
<hw>Si"lence</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. L.
<ets>silentium</ets>. See <er>Silent</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The state of being silent; entire absence of sound
or noise; absolute stillness.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I saw and heared; for such a numerous host⟦br⟧
Fled not in <qex>silence</qex> through the frighted deep.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Forbearance from, or absence of, speech;
taciturnity; muteness.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Secrecy; <as>as, these things were transacted in
<ex>silence</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The administration itself keeps a profound <qex>silence</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>D. Webster.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The cessation of rage, agitation, or tumult;
calmness; quiet; <as>as, the elements were reduced to
<ex>silence</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Absence of mention; oblivion.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And what most merits fame, in <qex>silence</qex> hid.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Silence</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Silence
<hw>Si"lence</hw>, <pos>interj.</pos> <def>Be silent; -- used
elliptically for <xex>let there be silence</xex>, or <xex>keep
silence</xex>.</def> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Silence</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Silence
<hw>Si"lence</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Silenced</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Silencing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
compel to silence; to cause to be still; to still; to hush.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Silence</qex> that dreadful bell; it frights the isle.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To put to rest; to quiet.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This would <qex>silence</qex> all further opposition.</q>
<rj><qau>Clarendon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>These would have <qex>silenced</qex> their scruples.</q>
<rj><qau>Rogers.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To restrain from the exercise of any function,
privilege of instruction, or the like, especially from the act of
preaching; <as>as, to <ex>silence</ex> a minister of the
gospel</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Rev. Thomas Hooker of Chelmsford, in Essex, was
<qex>silenced</qex> for nonconformity.</q> <rj><qau>B.
Trumbull.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To cause to cease firing, as by a vigorous
cannonade; <as>as, to <ex>silence</ex> the batteries of an
enemy</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Silencer</ent>⟦br⟧
